I don&#x27;t understand the testcase they provide. It opens a window at <a href="https://ssl.comodo.com/" rel="nofollow">https://ssl.comodo.com/</a> and sends a message to it with `postMessage`. However, the whole point of postMessage is to provide cross-origin communication. Continuing, the message they send is:<p><pre><code>     {
        command: &quot;execCode&quot;,
        code:    &quot;alert(document.cookie)&quot;,
     }
</code></pre>
Apparently <a href="https://ssl.comodo.com/" rel="nofollow">https://ssl.comodo.com/</a> used to then proceed to execute that code. However, this is not a vulnerability in the browser, but in that website. Am I missing something? Was Chromodo breaking the `messageEvent.origin` property, breaking same-origin checks in JavaScript? Seems far-fetched.
